{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3970].
  {panel}

Much like confluence, and other foruming software, it's nice to be able to login to an application and see what has changed since you've been there last.

I was thinking in the Issue navigator, in the Dates and Times section, there could be a checkbox that plainly says " Created/Modified Since Last Login".  It would be great if this was fine-grained enough to appreciate the difference between 9am and 3pm on any given day.  Which is why I didn't suggest a re-use of existing fields, which (aside from hard coded values in the drop-downs) seem limited to dates only?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3953].
  {panel}

Add another option view to the Issue Navigator to give Issues in jelly tags so that you can take it and import into another JIRA instance.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3949].
  {panel}

The project summary page includes a section listing the number of "open" issues for each priority and assignee. The issues that Jira consider "open" is currently hard-coded as those with a status of "Open", "Reopened" and "In Progress". I would like to include "Resolved" in this, but beyond editing the source code it is not currently possible to do this.

With configurable workflow (JRA-2580) and the ability to create extra issues statuses, the configuration of what is considered "open" will become even more important.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3935].
  {panel}

I'd like to have a daily email or report listing all the changes in JIRA issues -- creation, modification, commented, etc.

Confluence has this and it's great -- if that was exactly what we had in JIRA we would be thrilled.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3933].
  {panel}

It would be really helpful to be able to populate custom mail headers in the email notifications.

We'd like to populate two custom headers, say, X-JIRA-PROJECT and X-JIRA-ISSUE with the project and the issue number.  Then our mail clients could sort and group by those two header fields. Possibly we'd also want to add priority or custom fields into these headers.

Another option would be to fill in the In-Response-To header so that messages thread properly, but I'm not sure if that would work as well.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3910].
  {panel}

Our managers need to see issues they reported with assignees detailed on their dashboard.

How can we set up this?

Looks like either a new portlet needed, or set of fields shown for user filters should be customized.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3855].
  {panel}

JIRA 2.6 has a release notes generator. However its design assumes a human will cut/paste the notes somewhere. Many people want to suck in release notes during an automated (eg. Ant-driven) release process, and would like a *single* URL that fetches *just* the release notes in text or HTML format.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3845].
  {panel}

From a customer:

"*Procedures and policies for issue management* - I was stunned not to find this.  Perhaps it is there, and I've just missed it.  I find no documentation on setting up an environment in which JIRA can be used effectively.  Such a document should include things like "search the bug list before submitting a new one", etc. etc.  All the typical procedures that all your customers will have to put into place.  

Writing this stuff, and making it available (perhaps with a license: you may use this documentation if you have a license for JIRA), would make even more managers want to buy your product - it makes our lives easier.  Of course, we will want to adapt the documentation, but these kinds of guidelines are pretty general and embraced by most that use this kind of product.  I am a strong believer in reuse.  It strikes me that all of your customers are doing something similar here.  Prime refactoring material."

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3838].
  {panel}

It would be great if you could associate a default issue security level to project components, rather than just at the project level.

We have projects where certain components are classified as "internal", and issues filed against those components should not be client-visible.  While we can set the security level on each issue individually, it's all to easy to forget when entering a new bug.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3834].
  {panel}

Currently, our JIRA velocity notification templates are full of ghastly constructs like:

${constantsManager.getIssueType($issue.getString("type")).getString("name")}

to access the issue type. We really shouldn't be accessing internal APIs in velocity any more than using scriptlets in JSP.  We should have a wrapper object passed in the velocity context, that exposes each field (incl. custom fields) as simple ${issue.fieldname} properties.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3822].
  {panel}

We want to generate release notes only for public issues not for internal.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3786].
  {panel}

It would be nice if JIRA could resend notification emails for a given period.  For instance, when notification mails get dropped by a misconfigured SMTP server or JIRA instance.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3781].
  {panel}

User list is not alphabetically sorted. Is it sorted randomly?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3762].
  {panel}

When creating a new bug and you have leads setup for each component and have the default assignment setup to those component leads, if a person creates a new bug and assigned multiple components and the "Assign To" field is set to "Automatic", then the person that is assigned to the bug is the 1st component lead in the list of selected components. We would expect (or want) the "Automatic" assignment to choose the Project Lead since they're in the best position to decide who should fix this issue.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3735].
  {panel}

It would be very convenient to let me choose which groups a new user is a member of at the same time I create one. Right now I have to go through several extra steps to create anyone who isn't just a plain jira user.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3731].
  {panel}

When an issue is deemed to be a duplicate of another, and closed with Resolution: Duplicate, the votes ought to be transferred.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3705].
  {panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3699].
  {panel}

I've just added a comment but accidentally set the visibility to a group of which I am not a member.  Therefore I cannot see this comment!  As admin, I also cannot see the comment.

I can, as admin, add myself temporarily to that group to delete the comment, but it seems that admin perhaps should be able to see all comments regardless of their visibility.  This might also be useful for managers of large teams.

Therefore I propose a new permission 'View all comments' which overrides the usual visibility of comments.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3661].
  {panel}

We have a global field that we would like to delete and make it only available to certain projects.  However, we do not want to lose the data that corresponds to the global field.  For example, it is a loan number firld and we don not want to lose the loan numbers for the issues that have already been created with that global field.

Is there a way to move the data to a new project specific field without losing it?  Maybe there is something that can be done through the database?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3658].
  {panel}

In order to print a page (and have it look nice) a user needs to click on the printer icon first.  This could be simplified by using a print style sheet reference on every page.  See this article:

http://www.alistapart.com/articles/goingtoprint/

This would load up a special style sheet only when a user is printing.  This would allow users to print any page without needed to go through the step of choosing the printer friendly page.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3648].
  {panel}

When JIRA Professional is fed a JIRA Enterprise license key, it is quietly accepted and generally runs fine.  However things can break, if for instance the user later tries to upgrade JIRA, and the JIRA upgrade task relies on the license to determine whether to apply an enterprise-only upgrade.  We should therefore prevent people from running JIRA Professional with an Enterprise key.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3633].
  {panel}

We should have a SOAP / HTTP service that can take the values passed from the commitinfo script and determine whether the commit is valid or not.

In most cases a valid commit needs a JIRA issue number, or some keywords ('refactoring', 'UI changes').

We can then write a perl/python/exe script to post that information from CVSROOT/commitinfo.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3632].
  {panel}

I generally required to generate many issues at once. On these occasions, I do not necessary check that the issues I have created are actually created. However, in the situation where the disk space is full or at 100% usage on the server that we installed Jira, the cases are not being created. Since there is no warning or error message to warn that the disk space is, I only realize that all my cases that I thought I have generated did not. It will be nice if a warning or error message get generated in this situation.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3619].
  {panel}

JIRA should have an option to verify that a user owns the email address they claim to have, when signing up for an account.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3594].
  {panel}

It would be nice to be able to add a description of an attachment when you attach it (instead of just a general comment).  This description would appear in the Manage Attachments table next to the attachment.

Currently you can enter a general comment but that gets lost in the comment list and is difficult to locate when viewing the list of attachments.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3556].
  {panel}

It would be nice to have the ability to draw/paint on screenshots in the screenshot applet.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3536].
  {panel}

Release Notes should say "won't fix" for items that are resolved, but will not be addressed.

Right now, it looks like that item has been fixed.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3533].
  {panel}

The performance and the usability can be improved by using JavaScript in the dialog "Schedule Versions".

The buttons "first", "later" etc. can be implemented with JavaScript without a HTML Post to the application server. 

If the user has reschuduled the version, he will press the buttons "OK" and "Abort".

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3526].
  {panel}

It would be of great value to have the option to generate release notes categorized by component (or perhaps other fields).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3493].
  {panel}

The Attach screenshot feature currently stores images as jpg files. 

If it would store them as a raster oriented format such as png or gif the screenshots would look better and use less disk space.

I think this is a trivial change.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3477].
  {panel}

When working with the Excel export of the Time Tracking Report it would be GREAT if I had the version target and resource (person) available to help me sort and group.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3474].
  {panel}

We would like the ability to create release notes based on multiple 'versions' rather than just one for a project.

We add an entry for each build we make and eventually one of these builds becomes the release.  The release notes encompass all resolved issues since the last release which encompasses many builds. (and thus many versions)

Creating release notes for each version and compiling them into one master list is tedious and somewhat time-consuming.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3468].
  {panel}

I'd love to have that ;-)

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3467].
  {panel}

For large systems, it would be good to be able to quickly search for users.

If we index these using Lucene, then we can search for them very quickly.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3462].
  {panel}

When 'Assigned' was moved out of workflow, one result is that it is no longer possible to see which issues are assigned in the project road map.  It would be nice to display the old 'assigned' icon for Open Assigned issues.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3432].
  {panel}

Currently every registered user can view the email address of any other user with ViewProfile.jspa. Is there any option with which this can be disallowed for certain users groups?

If not please add such an option.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3413].
  {panel}

Now administrator have to go to every single project and add it to project category.

I think that it will be eaiser if multiple projects can be added to single category on "View Project Categories" page.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3400].
  {panel}

Having successfully got the CVS Log integration working again for the XDoclet JIRA, I noticed that there were a number of mail messages accumulating in the relevant POP3 account.  This is because the CVS commit logs are mailed to the developer's mailing list, and the other messages on the list aren't processed by the CVS Log (or any other) MessageHandler.  However, the mailbox in question has a 20 Meg limit, and at some point in the future it will start bouncing messages if nothing is done to delete the extra messages.  It would be nice, therefore, if there was a MessageHandler which deleted all the messages older than a specified number of days, so I could set up a service to clear out the surplus ones.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3385].
  {panel}

After configuring a new POP3/IMAP server, it would be useful to be able to check that I've typed in the password etc. correctly.  In addition to the Edit & Del links, an option to Test a connection (which would login to the server, possibly list any available messages, then disconnect) would enable this.  Otherwise, I have to wait for the CVS log integration (or other service that uses it) to work (or not) in order to know if I've got it configured right.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3377].
  {panel}

I'm using LdapCredProvider for authentication but I still want to add users to the system.  If I specify ext. user management, I cannot add more users to the system.  I have to ext user mgmt off and then add users and then turn it back on again.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3376].
  {panel}

It would be useful for the default POP3 Create Issue Handler to support more of the Issue fields via X-Headers.  For instance, it would be nice to be able to set the component(s) by adding "X-Component:" headers to the mail message, similar to the way that priority is handled already.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3353].
  {panel}

I like to have due-dates/scheduled release dates for versions. It helps us (using a tight schedule) in knowing when all issues of a certain release should be fixed.

When creating a version, add a description of what is going to be in that release (i.e. improve usability, add release notes), so people know what is coming.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3330].
  {panel}

We have a JIRA installation with about 20 projects. 4 of them is in a project category. This category is shown normaly when having the "Projects" portlet on the dashboard. But I have customized my dashboard so I only see the projects that I'm a developer on (about 8). I'm also a developer on all of the 4 projects in the project category. But because I'm using 8 "Project" portlets I'm not seeing any project category.

It would be nice if the project category feature also would display when using the "Project" portlets.

Of cause I can imagine that some people would not like this feature. So maybe it should be possible to select if project categories should be shown or not. I'm not sure how this should be done - maybe in the users profile or by using a special portlet?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3308].
  {panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3299].
  {panel}

When viewing a list of filters (eihter on the dashboard in the "Saved Filters" portlet or on the "Manage Filters" page) the list should also display the project that the filters search in.

This is especialy interesting when your JIRA installation holds a lot of projects. When a user for instance want a filter for each project that the user is a developer on that shows his or hers issues that has to be done by the next version, then the filter has to be named something like: "My issues for the next version of PROJECTNAME". The project name has to be a part of the filter name so the user can tell them apart or just know which filter is for what project.

Special conditions: If the filter search all projects then the text should say something like "All" and maybe be in itallic font.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3288].
  {panel}

This is a placeholder task to use for CVS commits.

We should move all GenericValues to be wrapped by objects, so that the end user code does not see the GenericValues.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3234].
  {panel}

When we setup our mail server to integrate with JIRA we gave it a default email address to use to send messages.  The problem with this is that when a message fails to get sent, the message delivery failure gets sent to the generic email address and the user doesnt know it fails.  Is there a way to set it up so that when an email is sent it uses the email address of the person logged in?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3230].
  {panel}

It would be nice if "versions" had due dates (for example 7.2 alpha is due on 1/3/04), and if all the "issues" (say bugs) for that version could inherit it's due date or something.

Perhaps when changing the due date on the version, it could prompt for which related issues to update.  This would mean that you wouldn't have to go and change say 30 issues' due dates manually (UGH!)

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3228].
  {panel}

In many projects the components get released seperately and so need their own version numbers. Project versions then become a list of the components at their particular version numbers.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3208].
  {panel}

After much discussion, we added a "Refactoring" issue type. The icon that we chose is a page with a small heart on it. While it seems that Improvement could be used, refactoring and improving are really different things. It would be nice to see this in the default configuration (it's easier to remove an issue type than to add one, at least if you want a cute icon).
